&lt;p&gt;If vectors are written without vector notation it represents the magnitude of the vector.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;hr /&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Time Derivatives are represented by a “.” above them &lt;br /&gt;
&lt;script type=&quot;math/tex&quot;&gt;\dot{\vec{r}}=\frac{d \vec{r}}{dt}&lt;/script&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;script type=&quot;math/tex&quot;&gt;\ddot{\vec{r}}=\frac{d^2 \vec{r}}{dt^2}&lt;/script&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;hr /&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Now, Equation of Motion
&lt;br /&gt; &lt;script type=&quot;math/tex&quot;&gt;\vec{F_1}=m_1 \dot{\vec{r_1}} ̇ ……(1)&lt;/script&gt;
&lt;br /&gt; &lt;script type=&quot;math/tex&quot;&gt;\vec{F_1}=\frac{Gm_1 m_2} {|r_{21} |^2}\hat{r_{21}}=\frac{Gm_1 m_2} {|r_{21} |^3}\vec{r_{21}}=-\left(\frac{Gm_1 m_2}{|r_{12}|^3}\right)\vec{r_{12}}&lt;/script&gt;
&lt;br /&gt; Putting this value in (1) gives&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;script type=&quot;math/tex&quot;&gt;\ddot{\vec{r_1}}=-\left(\frac{Gm_2}{r_{12}^3} \right)\vec{r_{12}}……(2)&lt;/script&gt;
&lt;br /&gt; Similarly&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;script type=&quot;math/tex&quot;&gt;\ddot{\vec{r_2}}=-\left(\frac{Gm_1}{r_{21}^3} \right)\vec{r_{21}}……(3)&lt;/script&gt;
&lt;br /&gt; From (2) and (3)&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;script type=&quot;math/tex&quot;&gt;m_1 \ddot{\vec{r_1}}+m_2 \ddot{\vec{r_2}}=0&lt;/script&gt;
&lt;br /&gt; Double Integrating&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;script type=&quot;math/tex&quot;&gt;m_1 \vec{r_1}+m_2\vec {r_2}=ct+d&lt;/script&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;If we divide by $$m_1+m_2$$ we get $$r_{CM}$$ Since it is a linear function of t we can say that C.O.M. travels in a straight line.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
Subtracting (3) from (2). We get position vector of first body w.r.t. second body.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;script type=&quot;math/tex&quot;&gt;\ddot{\vec{r_{12} }}=\ddot{\vec{r_1}}-\ddot{\vec{r_2}}=-\left(\frac{G}{r_{12}^3}\right)\left(m_2 \vec{r_{12}}-m_1 \vec{r_{21}}\right)&lt;/script&gt;
&lt;br /&gt; Represent &lt;script type=&quot;math/tex&quot;&gt;\vec{r_{12}}=-\vec{r_{21}}=\vec{r}&lt;/script&gt; , &lt;script type=&quot;math/tex&quot;&gt;|r_{12}|=r&lt;/script&gt; and &lt;script type=&quot;math/tex&quot;&gt;μ=G(m_1+m_2)&lt;/script&gt; &lt;br /&gt;
&lt;script type=&quot;math/tex&quot;&gt;⇒\ddot{\vec{r}}+\frac{μ}{r^3}  \vec{r}=0&lt;/script&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;hr /&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
Take cross product with &lt;script type=&quot;math/tex&quot;&gt;\vec{r}&lt;/script&gt; .
&lt;br /&gt; Gives
&lt;br /&gt; &lt;script type=&quot;math/tex&quot;&gt;\ddot{\vec{r}}\times{\vec{r}}=0&lt;/script&gt;
&lt;br /&gt; Also &lt;script type=&quot;math/tex&quot;&gt;\frac{d}{dr}\left(\dot{\vec{r}}×\vec{r}\right)=\ddot{\vec{r}}\times\vec{r}&lt;/script&gt; .
&lt;br /&gt; Therefore Angular momentum per unit mass is constant i.e. &lt;script type=&quot;math/tex&quot;&gt;\dot{\vec{r}}\times\vec{r}=h&lt;/script&gt; 
&lt;br /&gt; Where &lt;script type=&quot;math/tex&quot;&gt;h&lt;/script&gt; is a constant. Also Motion is planar since orbital plane is fixed. Polar coordinates can be used.
&lt;br /&gt; Some Points
&lt;br /&gt; &lt;script type=&quot;math/tex&quot;&gt;\vec{r}={r} \hat{r}&lt;/script&gt;
&lt;script type=&quot;math/tex&quot;&gt;\dot{\vec{r}}=\dot{r}\hat{r}+{r}\dot{\hat{r}}&lt;/script&gt;
&lt;script type=&quot;math/tex&quot;&gt;\dot{\hat{r}}=\dot{θ}\hat{θ}&lt;/script&gt; &lt;script type=&quot;math/tex&quot;&gt;\dot{\hat{θ}}=-\dot{θ}\hat{r}&lt;/script&gt;
&lt;br /&gt; This gives
&lt;script type=&quot;math/tex&quot;&gt;\dot{\vec{r}}=\dot{r}\hat{r}+{r}\dot{\theta}\hat{θ}&lt;/script&gt;
&lt;br /&gt; &lt;script type=&quot;math/tex&quot;&gt;\ddot{\vec{r}}=\left(\ddot{r}-r\dot{θ}^2 \right)\hat{r}+\left(2\dot{r}\dot{θ}+r\ddot{θ}\right) \hat{θ}&lt;/script&gt;
&lt;br /&gt; Now putting in above derived equation
&lt;br /&gt;&lt;script type=&quot;math/tex&quot;&gt;\ddot{\vec{r}}+\frac{\mu\hat{r}}{r^2}=0&lt;/script&gt;
&lt;br /&gt; &lt;script type=&quot;math/tex&quot;&gt;\ddot{\vec{r}}=-\left(\frac{\mu}{r^2}\right)\hat{r}&lt;/script&gt;
&lt;br /&gt; &lt;script type=&quot;math/tex&quot;&gt;\left(\ddot{r}-r\dot{θ}^2 \right)\hat{r}+\left(2\dot{r}\dot{θ}+r\ddot{θ}\right)\hat{θ}=-\left(\frac{\mu}{r^2}\right)\hat{r}&lt;/script&gt;
&lt;br /&gt; Comparing
&lt;br /&gt; &lt;script type=&quot;math/tex&quot;&gt;\ddot{r}-r\dot{θ}^2 =-\left(\frac{\mu}{r^2}\right)......(4)&lt;/script&gt;
&lt;br /&gt; &lt;script type=&quot;math/tex&quot;&gt;2\dot{r}\dot{θ}+r\ddot{θ}=0......(5)&lt;/script&gt;
&lt;br /&gt; in (5), Multiply both sides by &lt;script type=&quot;math/tex&quot;&gt;r&lt;/script&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;&lt;script type=&quot;math/tex&quot;&gt;2r\dot{r}\dot{θ}+r^2\ddot{θ}=0&lt;/script&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;&lt;script type=&quot;math/tex&quot;&gt;\frac{d(r^2\dot{\theta})}{dt}=0&lt;/script&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;&lt;script type=&quot;math/tex&quot;&gt;r^2\dot{\theta}=h&lt;/script&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;&lt;script type=&quot;math/tex&quot;&gt;h&lt;/script&gt; is same constant that we got earlier. Just writing it in different way.&lt;br /&gt;
Now for (4)&lt;br /&gt;
Substitute &lt;script type=&quot;math/tex&quot;&gt;r=1/u&lt;/script&gt;
&lt;br /&gt; &lt;script type=&quot;math/tex&quot;&gt;\dot{r}=\frac{-1}{u^2}\cdot\dot{\theta}\left(\frac{du}{d\theta}\right)&lt;/script&gt;
&lt;br /&gt; &lt;script type=&quot;math/tex&quot;&gt;\dot{r}=-r^2\dot{\theta}\left(\frac{du}{d\theta}\right)&lt;/script&gt;
&lt;br /&gt; from earlier &lt;script type=&quot;math/tex&quot;&gt;r^2\dot{\theta}=h&lt;/script&gt;
&lt;br /&gt; &lt;script type=&quot;math/tex&quot;&gt;\dot{r}=-h\left(\frac{du}{d\theta}\right)&lt;/script&gt;
&lt;br /&gt; &lt;script type=&quot;math/tex&quot;&gt;\Rightarrow\ddot{r}=-h\dot{\theta}\left(\frac{d^2u}{d{\theta}^2}\right)&lt;/script&gt;
&lt;br /&gt; Now (4) becomes
&lt;br /&gt; &lt;script type=&quot;math/tex&quot;&gt;h\dot{\theta}\left(\frac{d^2u}{d{\theta}^2}\right)-\frac^2}{u}=-\mu u^2&lt;/script&gt;
&lt;br /&gt; Simplyfying and using &lt;script type=&quot;math/tex&quot;&gt;\dot{\theta}=u^2h&lt;/script&gt;. We get
&lt;br /&gt; &lt;script type=&quot;math/tex&quot;&gt;\frac{d^2u}{d\theta^2}+u=\frac{\mu}{h^2}&lt;/script&gt;
&lt;br /&gt; Solving This gives
&lt;br /&gt; &lt;script type=&quot;math/tex&quot;&gt;u=\frac{\mu}{h^2}\left(1+cos(\theta-\overline{\omega})\right)&lt;/script&gt;
&lt;br /&gt; &lt;script type=&quot;math/tex&quot;&gt;\Rightarrow r=\frac{\frac{h^2}{\mu}}{1+cos(\theta-\overline{\omega})}&lt;/script&gt;
&lt;br /&gt; &lt;script type=&quot;math/tex&quot;&gt;\Rightarrow r=\frac{p}{1+{e}\cdot cos(\theta-{\omega})}=\frac{p}{1+{e}\cdot cos f}&lt;/script&gt;
&lt;br /&gt; Here &lt;script type=&quot;math/tex&quot;&gt;e&lt;/script&gt; is eccentricity, &lt;script type=&quot;math/tex&quot;&gt;f&lt;/script&gt; is true anamoly or angle measured from major axis from closest distance of approach (Pericentre).
&lt;br /&gt; &lt;script type=&quot;math/tex&quot;&gt;p=\frac{h^2}{\mu}&lt;/script&gt;, 
&lt;br /&gt; &lt;script type=&quot;math/tex&quot;&gt;p&lt;/script&gt; represents Semi-Latus Rectum of the orbit. 
&lt;br /&gt; Centre is position of sun/star.
&lt;br /&gt;&lt;center&gt;======================image=======================&lt;/center&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt; Planets have elliptical orbits because all other paths lead planets to be thrown away.&lt;/p&gt;

